# Comprehensive Text-Based Wrestling Promotion Game Features

## ROSTER MANAGEMENT (1-12)

### 1. Wrestler Scouting System
Discover new talent through multiple channels including independent promotions, international circuits, amateur wrestling backgrounds, athletic crossovers, and social media sensations. Each source provides different talent types with varying costs and potential.

### 2. Contract Negotiations
Detailed negotiation system where wrestlers have demands based on their perceived value. Factors include base salary, contract length, downside guarantees, appearance bonuses, and main event clauses.

### 3. Contract Length Options
Offer contracts ranging from per-appearance deals to multi-year exclusive agreements. Longer contracts provide security but lock in salary; shorter deals offer flexibility but risk losing talent.

### 4. Performance Bonuses
Structure bonus payments for title wins, main event appearances, merchandise sales thresholds, match of the night awards, and PPV participation.

### 5. Creative Control Clauses
Top stars may demand input on their character direction, finish protection, or approval over who they lose to. Refusing may cost you the signing; accepting limits your booking freedom.

### 6. No-Compete Clauses
Include clauses preventing wrestlers from appearing on competing shows for specified periods after contract expiration. Affects negotiation difficulty and wrestler willingness.

### 7. Merchandise Split Arrangements
Negotiate percentage splits on wrestler-specific merchandise. Higher percentages attract talent but reduce company profits.

### 8. Exclusive vs Open Contracts
Decide whether wrestlers work exclusively for your promotion or can take independent bookings. Exclusive costs more but protects your investment.

### 9. Contract Renewal System
Track contract expiration dates with automated alerts. Wrestlers become free agents if not renewed, opening them to competitor offers.

### 10. Wrestler Release Mechanics
Release underperforming or problematic talent with options for mutual release, future endeavors, or immediate termination. Each has reputation and financial implications.

### 11. Roster Size Management
Balance roster size against budget and TV time. Too many wrestlers means unhappy underutilized talent; too few limits booking options.

### 12. Roster Tier Classification
Categorize wrestlers into main eventers, upper midcard, midcard, lower card, and enhancement talent. Affects booking expectations and salary demands.

