## WRESTLER ATTRIBUTES (13-25)

### 13. In-Ring Technical Skill
Measures wrestling ability including holds, counters, transitions, and chain wrestling. Affects match quality ratings and ability to carry lesser opponents.

### 14. Charisma Rating
Natural ability to connect with audiences without speaking. Influences crowd reactions, merchandise sales, and organic popularity growth.

### 15. Microphone Ability
Promo delivery skills including timing, emotion, and authenticity. Critical for building feuds and maintaining character work during talking segments.

### 16. Physical Appearance
Overall look including physique, height, attractiveness, and presence. Affects first impressions, marketability, and credibility in certain roles.

### 17. Stamina Rating
Endurance for long matches and demanding schedules. Low stamina wrestlers tire quickly, affecting late-match performance and injury risk.

### 18. Popularity/Overness
Current connection with your specific audience. Built through wins, storylines, and exposure. Determines crowd reactions and drawing power.

### 19. Ring Psychology
Understanding of storytelling within matches including selling, timing, drama building, and reading crowd reactions for adjustment.

### 20. High Flying Ability
Capability for aerial maneuvers. Enables spectacular spots but increases injury risk. Required for certain match types.

### 21. Power/Strength Rating
Physical strength for power moves, slams, and believable dominance. Affects move set options and credibility against larger opponents.

### 22. Hardcore Wrestling Skill
Proficiency with weapons, extreme spots, and brawling. Necessary for gimmick matches but increases injury probability.

### 23. Star Quality/IT Factor
Intangible presence that makes someone feel special. Affects ceiling potential and audience willingness to accept them in top positions.

### 24. Consistency Rating
Reliability of performance night to night. Inconsistent wrestlers may have great or terrible matches unpredictably.

### 25. Safety Record
How carefully they work to protect opponents. Unsafe workers cause more injuries to others, creating backstage issues.

